You don&#39;t initialise `back` here:

     Link *front = list, *back;

and the only assignment to `back` may not execute due to its being conditional:

    while (front-&gt;ptr) {   // This condition could be false...
        back = front;      // ... in which case this doesn&#39;t happen.
        front = front-&gt;ptr;
    }

which would cause you to dereference an uninitialised `back` here:

    back-&gt;ptr = 0;

It is a good idea to always initialise variables.

You also need a special case for the singleton list, where you should return the null pointer.  

If you initialise `back` to the null pointer, it will be null exactly when you have a list with only one element.

Something like this:


    Link *popBack(Link *list, int &amp;val) {
            if (!list) return nullptr;
    
            Link *front = list, *back = nullptr;
            while (front-&gt;ptr) {
                back = front;
                front = front-&gt;ptr;
            }
            val = front-&gt;data;
            delete front;

            if (!back)
            {
                return nullptr;
            }
            else 
            {
                back-&gt;ptr = 0;
                return list;
            }
    }

